<h2 id="basic-commands">Basic Commands</h2>
<p>Letâ€™s go over some basic commands.</p>

<h3 id="pwd">pwd</h3>
<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">pwd</code> prints the working directory telling the user where they are in the filesystem.</p>

<p><img src="photos/Bash&amp;CLI/pwd.png" alt="pwd" /></p>

<h3 id="ls">ls</h3>
<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ls</code> lists a directoryâ€™s contents. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ls</code> like many other Unix-like commands can take on arguments, options, and parameters. (More about this later)</p>

<p><img src="photos/Bash&amp;CLI/ls.png" alt="pwd" /></p>

<h3 id="cd">cd</h3>
<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">cd</code> stands for change directory. As the commandâ€™s name says, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">cd</code> changes into directories within the Linux filesystem. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">cd</code> can take in special characters like <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.</code>,  <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">..</code>, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">-</code> or an absolute or relative path for its argument.</p>

